\section{Open Questions}

Open questions need the prompt and a character limit, and they can optionally
carry a markdown fence language for uploaded file bodies.  The limit belongs to
the question data because it affects both the HTTP form and the canonical hash.
The fence hint also belongs here, but it has to be a single CommonMark info word:
whitespace or backticks would change the structure of the generated fence rather
than just its language tag.  We omit the hint from the canonical JSON when it is
unset so existing open-question hashes stay byte-for-byte stable.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class OpenQuestion:
    """An open-text question with a character cap.

    The optional fence language tags uploaded file bodies as
    fenced Markdown.
    """

    text: str
    max_chars: int = 280
    fence: str | None = None
    kind: str = "open"

    def __post_init__(self):
        if self.max_chars <= 0:
            raise ValueError("open questions need a positive character limit")
        if self.fence is not None and (
            not self.fence
            or any(char.isspace() or char == "`" for char in self.fence)
        ):
            raise ValueError(
                "markdown fence language must be a non-empty word "
                "without whitespace or backticks"
            )

    def to_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
        """Return a JSON-friendly representation of the question."""

        result = {
            "kind": self.kind,
            "text": self.text,
            "max_chars": self.max_chars,
        }
        if self.fence is not None:
            result["fence"] = self.fence
        return result
@

The limit validation is small, but it is what protects the rest of the system
from impossible forms:

<<test functions>>=
def test_open_question_requires_positive_limit():
    with pytest.raises(ValueError):
        OpenQuestion("Feedback?", max_chars=0)


@pytest.mark.parametrize("fence", ["", "python code", "python\n", "py`thon"])
def test_open_question_rejects_malformed_fence_languages(fence):
    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match="fence language"):
        OpenQuestion("Q", fence=fence)


def test_open_question_to_dict_omits_an_unset_fence():
    assert OpenQuestion("Q").to_dict() == {
        "kind": "open",
        "text": "Q",
        "max_chars": 280,
    }


def test_open_question_to_dict_includes_a_configured_fence():
    assert OpenQuestion("Q", fence="python").to_dict() == {
        "kind": "open",
        "text": "Q",
        "max_chars": 280,
        "fence": "python",
    }
